            <span class="timeline-dot"></span>
            <div class="timeline-content">
              <span class="timeline-era">The Command Line</span>
              <span class="timeline-desc">Teletypes and CRT monitors created the first real-time human-machine dialogue. FORTRAN, COBOL, BASIC made programming approachable. UNIX introduced composable tools. MS-DOS put the CLI on every desk. <em>Powerful and unlimited &mdash; but demanded you learn the machine's grammar.</em></span>
              <span class="timeline-tag">UNIX &middot; MS-DOS &middot; Teletype &middot; CRT &middot; Shell</span>
            </div>
          </a>

          <a href="#visionaries" class="timeline-item">
            <span class="timeline-year">1973</span>
            <span class="timeline-dot"></span>
            <div class="timeline-content">
              <span class="timeline-era">The GUI Is Born</span>
              <span class="timeline-desc">Xerox PARC built the Alto &mdash; bitmapped display, mouse, overlapping windows, icons. The WIMP paradigm. The key insight: <em>humans are not command parsers &mdash; we think in spaces, objects, and actions.</em> Xerox invented the future but couldn't sell it.</span>
              <span class="timeline-tag">Xerox PARC &middot; Alto &middot; WIMP &middot; Mouse &middot; Bitmapped Display</span>
            </div>
          </a>

          <a href="#the-war" class="timeline-item">
            <span class="timeline-year">1984–95</span>
            <span class="timeline-dot"></span>
            <div class="timeline-content">
              <span class="timeline-era">The GUI Wars</span>
              <span class="timeline-desc">Five factions intercepted PARC's vision. Apple bet vertical integration. Microsoft bet horizontal scale and won the desktop. UNIX built the technically elegant X Window System. Commodore/Atari had the best price-performance. Xerox priced itself into irrelevance. <em>The GUI made computers accessible to everyone &mdash; but introduced a ceiling.</em></span>
              <span class="timeline-tag">Macintosh &middot; Windows 95 &middot; X11 &middot; AmigaOS &middot; Xerox Star</span>
            </div>
          </a>

          <a href="#connected-world" class="timeline-item">
            <span class="timeline-year">1990s</span>
            <span class="timeline-dot"></span>
            <div class="timeline-content">
              <span class="timeline-era">The Web</span>
              <span class="timeline-desc">Berners-Lee's World Wide Web turned the interface into a shared, linked document. The browser became the universal client. Web apps blurred the line between "using a website" and "using software." <em>You were no longer interacting with local files &mdash; but with servers across the world.</em></span>
              <span class="timeline-tag">HTTP &middot; HTML &middot; Browsers &middot; AJAX &middot; SPA</span>
            </div>
          </a>

          <a href="#connected-world" class="timeline-item">
            <span class="timeline-year">2007</span>
            <span class="timeline-dot"></span>
            <div class="timeline-content">
              <span class="timeline-era">Touch & Mobile</span>
              <span class="timeline-desc">The iPhone removed the last physical intermediary. No mouse, no stylus &mdash; you touched the interface directly. Pinch, swipe, tap mapped to actions humans already knew. By 2015, mobile surpassed desktop. <em>The computer moved into your pocket &mdash; always present, always on.</em></span>
              <span class="timeline-tag">iPhone &middot; Multi-touch &middot; App Store &middot; Responsive Design</span>
            </div>
          </a>

          <a href="#false-start" class="timeline-item">
            <span class="timeline-year">2015</span>
            <span class="timeline-dot"></span>
            <div class="timeline-content">
              <span class="timeline-era">The Chatbot False Start</span>
              <span class="timeline-desc">Facebook Messenger Platform, Microsoft Bot Framework &mdash; everyone promised natural language interfaces. But the bots were decision trees in a text input costume. If you said something unexpected, they broke. <em>A text input is not the same as understanding language. The desire was real, the technology wasn't.</em></span>
              <span class="timeline-tag">Messenger Bots &middot; Intent Classification &middot; Rigid Dialogue</span>
            </div>
          </a>

          <a href="#cli-never-died" class="timeline-item">
            <span class="timeline-year">Ongoing</span>
            <span class="timeline-dot"></span>
            <div class="timeline-content">
              <span class="timeline-era">The CLI Never Died</span>
              <span class="timeline-desc">While the world clicked and tapped, the command line became invisible infrastructure. Every cloud deployment, CI/CD pipeline, container, and git workflow runs on CLIs. <em>Text is composable. GUIs are for human eyeballs. CLIs are for both humans and machines.</em></span>
              <span class="timeline-tag">aws &middot; docker &middot; kubectl &middot; terraform &middot; git</span>
            </div>
          </a>

          <a href="#talking-to-air" class="timeline-item timeline-item--active">
            <span class="timeline-year">2024+</span>
            <span class="timeline-dot"></span>
            <div class="timeline-content">
              <span class="timeline-era">LLM & AI Agents</span>
              <span class="timeline-desc">Large Language Models finally solved natural language understanding. Developers don't open their editors. PMs query Claude Code for sprint status. Designers describe interactions in words. Under the hood, AI agents translate natural language into CLI commands and API calls. <em>The full stack is present: natural language at the top, CLI at the bottom. We didn't replace &mdash; we layered.</em></span>
              <span class="timeline-tag">GPT &middot; Claude &middot; Gemini &middot; AI Agents &middot; Natural Language</span>
            </div>
          </a>
        </div>
      </section>

    </div>
